  regions, disrupting transmission of electrochemical signals and causing
  cognitive and emotional dysfunction. Connectome-level mechanisms for how the
  brain compensates for injury have not been fully characterized. Here, we
  collected serial MRI-based structural and functional connectome metrics and
  neuropsychological scores in 26 mild traumatic brain injury subjects (29.4
  $\pm$ 8.0 years, 20 males) at 1 and 6 months postinjury. We quantified the
  relationship between functional and structural connectomes using network
  diffusion (ND) model propagation time, a measure that can be interpreted as
  how much of the structural connectome is being utilized for the spread of
  functional activation, as captured via the functional connectome. Overall
  cognition showed significant improvement from 1 to 6 months (t25 = -2.15, p =
