  has been used to examine the brain mechanisms of stroke patients with
  hemiplegia, but the relationship between functional connectivity (FC) and
  treatment-induced motor function recovery has not yet been fully
  investigated. This study aimed to identify the brain FC changes in stroke
  patients and study the relationship between FC and motor function assessment
  using the resting-state fMRI. METHODS: Seventeen stroke patients with
  hemiplegia and fifteen healthy control subjects (HCSs) were recruited in this
  study. We compared the FC between the ipsilesional primary motor cortex (M1)
