    Resting-state functional connectivity is used throughout neuroscience to
  study brain organization and to generate biomarkers of development, disease,
  and cognition. The processes that give rise to correlated activity are,
  however, poorly understood. Here we decompose resting-state functional
  connectivity using a temporal unwrapping procedure to assess the
  contributions of moment-to-moment activity cofluctuations to the overall
  connectivity pattern. This approach temporally resolves functional
  connectivity at a timescale of single frames, which enables us to make direct
  comparisons of cofluctuations of network organization with fluctuations in
  the blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) time series. We show that
  surprisingly, only a small fraction of frames exhibiting the strongest
  cofluctuation amplitude are required to explain a significant fraction of
  variance in the overall pattern of connection weights as well as the
