    The most difficult clinical questions in stroke rehabilitation are ``What
  is this patient's potential for recovery?'' and ``What is the best
  rehabilitation strategy for this person, given her/his clinical profile?''
  Without answers to these questions, clinicians struggle to make decisions
  regarding the content and focus of therapy, and researchers design studies
  that inadvertently mix participants who have a high likelihood of responding
  with those who do not. Developing and implementing biomarkers that
  distinguish patient subgroups will help address these issues and unravel the
  factors important to the recovery process. The goal of the present paper is
  to provide a consensus statement regarding the current state of the evidence
