    \field{abstract}{%
    Multivariate lesion behaviour mapping based on machine learning algorithms
  has recently been suggested to complement the methods of anatomo-behavioural
  approaches in cognitive neuroscience. Several studies applied and validated
  support vector regression-based lesion symptom mapping (SVR-LSM) to map
  anatomo-behavioural relations. However, this promising method, as well as the
  multivariate approach per se, still bears many open questions. By using large
  lesion samples in three simulation experiments, the present study empirically
  tested the validity of several methodological aspects. We found that (i)
  correction for multiple comparisons is required in the current implementation
  of SVR-LSM, (ii) that sample sizes of at least 100-120 subjects are required
  to optimally model voxel-wise lesion location in SVR-LSM, and (iii) that
  SVR-LSM is susceptible to misplacement of statistical topographies along the
  brain's vasculature to a similar extent as mass-univariate analyses.%
